  <section id="sec-17-formula-generalization">
  <h2>
   &sect;17. Formula Generalization &mdash; Sum-of-Costs Form
  </h2>
  <hr>
  <h3>
   &sect;17.1 &mdash; Overview
  </h3>
  <p>
   &sect;7 specifies the four gates governing admission of cost terms to the RCV integrand. This section presents the corresponding mathematical generalization of the RCV formula &mdash; the sum-of-costs form &mdash; and derives the properties (convergence, dimensional consistency, CS = RCV &minus; B preservation) that must hold for the generalization to be sound. The generalization is the extension that makes the framework generative: new variables can be admitted as the four gates reveal them, without destabilizing the mathematical architecture. The two-term RCV formula of &sect;3.1 is recovered as the n = 2 special case of the general form.
  </p>
  <h3>
   &sect;17.2 &mdash; The Generalization: Formal Statement
  </h3>
  <p>
   The two-term RCV formula (&sect;3.1):
  </p>
  <p>
   RCV(R, t0) = &int;t₀&infin;&nbsp;{ [1 &minus; S(t | t0)] &middot; U(R, t, Q(t)) + E(R, t) } &middot; D(t, t0) dt
  </p>
  <p>
   is replaced by the general sum-of-costs form:
  </p>
  <p>
   RCV(R, t0, Context) = &int;t₀&infin;&nbsp;{ &Sigma;i=1n&nbsp;Ci(R, t, Context) } &middot; D(t, t0) dt
  </p>
  <p>
   where:
  </p>
  <p>
   &bull; n is the number of cost terms admitted into the integrand under the current Context;
  </p>
  <p>
   &bull; each Ci&nbsp;has passed the four gates (&sect;7.1-&sect;7.4) under stated specifications;
  </p>
  <p>
   &bull; Context encodes the specific extraction situation (who captures value, who bears cost, what scarcity operates, what substitutability landscape exists, what externality profile, what community relationships are affected);
  </p>
  <p>
   &bull; D(t, t0) is the declining-rate discount factor per &sect;16.1.
  </p>
  <p>
   The two-term form is recovered as the special case n = 2 with C1(R, t, Context) = [1 &minus; S(t | t0)] &middot; U(R, t, Q(t)) (foreclosure) and C2(R, t, Context) = E(R, t) (externality tail). This equivalence is worked explicitly in &sect;17.6 below.
  </p>
  <h3>
   &sect;17.3 &mdash; Convergence Preservation
  </h3>
  <p>
   Claim.&nbsp;If each Ci&nbsp;satisfies the boundedness gate (Gate 3, &sect;7.3) individually under the stated discount factor, and n is finite, then the sum-of-costs integral converges.
  </p>
  <p>
   Proof.&nbsp;The integrand is a finite sum of functions, each of which yields a convergent integral under D by Gate 3 (&sect;7.3). By linearity of integration:
  </p>
  <p>
   &int;t₀&infin;&nbsp;&Sigma;i=1n&nbsp;Ci(R, t, Context) &middot; D(t, t0) dt = &Sigma;i=1n&nbsp;&int;t₀&infin;&nbsp;Ci(R, t, Context) &middot; D(t, t0) dt
  </p>
  <p>
   Each term on the right is finite (Gate 3 passes individually). A finite sum of finite terms is finite. The integral of the sum converges. Q.E.D.
  </p>
  <p>
   Remark on countable sums.&nbsp;For countably many Ci&nbsp;(a theoretical extension), uniform convergence of the partial sums plus absolute convergence of the sum of integrals is required. In practice, n is bounded by the empirical scope of CIT-discoverable variables in a given Context (observed bound &le; ~20 across 18 case studies). Countable-sum extensions are not required for the framework&rsquo;s current applied scope. Future research may address formal boundedness of n as a function of Context complexity; the current framework operates under empirical finiteness.
  </p>
  <p>
   Interchange of sum and integral.&nbsp;For finite sums, interchange is unconditional. For countable sums, the interchange requires a dominating function by the dominated convergence theorem or a monotone structure by the monotone convergence theorem. In the framework&rsquo;s applied scope (finite n), no dominating function is needed; the interchange is a standard result.
  </p>
  <h3>
   &sect;17.4 &mdash; Units Consistency
  </h3>
  <p>
